article.headline: With Anderson on bench, Benningfield leads Vandy
article.linkText: Foul-plagued Anderson cheers Vandy past Georgia
article.story:
NORTH LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) -- Foul trouble reduced Vanderbilt's leading scorer Chantelle Anderson to a cheerleader Friday at the Southeastern Conference Tournament.

Junior Jenni Benningfield gave her lots to cheer for, scoring 29 points to lead Vanderbilt (No. 16 ESPN/USA Today, No. 15 AP) to a 74-70 victory over Georgia (No. 19, No. 17) in the quarterfinal game.

"I knew I had to pick it up,'' Benningfield said. "The rest of the team knew they had to step up and do a little extra and we did that tonight. It wasn't just me.''

Benningfield made 12 of 23 shots from the field to lead a hot-shooting Vanderbilt team that made 58 percent (30-for-52). Vanderbilt, the first lower seed to win in two days, advanced to play LSU in the semifinals Saturday.

Anderson missed almost 14 minutes after picking up her fourth foul with 16:12 remaining and Vanderbilt (21-8) trailing 42-36.

   "I just wanted to be a leader,'' said Anderson, who finished with 14 points in just 17 minutes. "When they came to timeouts, I wanted to run out there and give them energy and keep cheering. That helped me stay in the game, so when I did go back in, I was into the game.''

Georgia (19-9) led by at least six points until about 10 minutes
remained, when Vanderbilt started to take command. Benningfield's
3-pointer cut the lead to 54-53 and Nicole Jules gave the
Commodores their first lead since late in the first half after a
shot-clock violation by the Lady Bulldogs.

	   The teams traded the lead back and forth until Hillary Hager put
the Commodores in front to stay at 64-62 with 3:12 to go.

Anderson came in soon after, making three straight baskets to
give Vanderbilt a 70-67 lead with 24 seconds remaining. She
deflected a 3-point attempt by Georgia's Christi Thomas 10 seconds
later.

"I didn't feel like I was sitting out so long,'' Anderson said. "I still felt like I was one with the team. That helped me step it up at the end.''

Hager, who finished with 11 points, grabbed the rebound after
Thomas' miss and made two free throws to seal the win.

Vanderbilt overcame some sloppy play, giving Georgia 23 points
off turnovers, and it was out-rebounded 36-26. The Lady Bulldogs
scored 17 points on offensive rebounds, compared to just two points for Vanderbilt.

"It was probably one of the worst first halves of the year and
halfway through the second half we still weren't playing well,''
first-year Commodores coach Melanie Balcomb said. "For some
reason, down the stretch, we really stepped up. Suddenly we were
getting deflections, we were checking out and doing the things we
hadn't done the whole game.''

Despite winning the rebound battle and making 10 of 21
3-pointers, Georgia couldn't overcome Benningfield and Anderson
down low.

"The difference in the basketball game was we were excellent
defensively on the perimeter but not as good as we needed to be
inside,'' Georgia coach Andy Landers said. "But Benningfield and
Anderson are both so very, very good that they're difficult to
defend.''

Freshman Alexis Kendrick paced Georgia with 21 points, while
Mary Beth Lycett had 20. Thomas, who came in averaging 15.9 points
per game, was held to six points and 11 rebounds.

Vanderbilt has shot the ball well inside the Alltel Arena. The Commodores made 60 percent from the field in a 74-58 win over Florida in the first round on Thursday.
